To estimate the parameters, the entire test section is modeled as shown in Fig. 3(b), excluding the insulation. The effect of gravity on the gas in neglected. This model addresses an axisymmetric problem and is thus represented as a narrow wedge (less than
5 °
), as presented in Fig. 5. The length of the model matches that of the test section, measuring 940 mm, and the height of the wedge corresponds to the tube’s radius, that is, 100 mm. The model includes a two-dimensional axisymmetric geometry, distinguishing between the packed bed (comprising wood particles) and the tube (made of iron). This choice allows a more accurate representation of radial heat losses and wall conduction effects.

Despite the relevance of the present findings, several limitations should be acknowledged. First, the experimental conditions were restricted to low Reynolds numbers (
Re < 61
) and moderate temperatures (below 347 K). Therefore, the applicability of the proposed correlations at higher flow rates and elevated temperatures, typical of industrial dryers, remains to be validated. Second, the range of initial moisture contents was relatively narrow, from 0.4% to 6.2% for wood pellets and from 0.4% to 9.1% for wood chips, which may not fully capture drying behavior under extreme humidity conditions. Third, the study considered a single-bed geometry and did not explore the influence of scale-up or potential bed heterogeneity. Furthermore, this study considers only two types of biomass particles: wood pellets and irregular wood chips. These shapes were chosen to reflect common geometries encountered in industrial applications. Wood pellets typically have a cylindrical shape with uniform size [3], while wood chips exhibit irregular, approximately rectangular shapes with greater dimensional variability [49]. Particle shape can influence the drying process through its effects on porosity, surface area-to-volume ratio, and local heat and mass transfer conditions. For instance, cylindrical particles generally provide more uniform packing and lower interstitial porosity (0.43), whereas irregular particles can lead to higher local porosity (0.47) and less homogeneous temperature and moisture fields. However, by using the concept of equivalent diameter, it is possible to characterize these diverse geometries within a common framework, allowing for meaningful comparison of bulk-scale thermal behavior. Moreover, since the present model employs a volume-averaged approach based on macroscopic parameters, local differences due to shape irregularities are inherently averaged out. Therefore, the influence of particle shape is captured indirectly through its impact on the effective parameters rather than requiring explicit geometric modeling. Future studies may benefit from coupling this approach with detailed pore-scale simulations or experimental imaging to further quantify the microscale influence of particle morphology on drying kinetics. Additionally, the model did not account for biomass shrinkage during drying, which can affect porosity and local transfer coefficients.
